Let's use the method of elimination to solve this system of equations.
Begin by manipulating $\text{\textwe}\leftarrow \text{equations}\right.\text{}$ in order to make the coefficients of $y$ in both equations opposites.
\begin{aligned}2x - y &= 5 \\ x + 2y &= 5\end{aligned}
Multiplying the second equation by $2$ will remove the coefficient of $y$ from both equations since $-1$ and $2$ are opposites.
\begin{aligned}2x - y &= 5 \\ 2x + 4y &= 10\end{aligned}
Now, let's subtract the second equation from the first equation to eliminate $y$.
\begin{aligned}(2x - y) - (2x + 4y) &= 5 - 10 \\ -5y &= -5\end{aligned}
Dividing both sides by $-5$, we get $y = 1$.
Now let's substitute $y = 1$ into $2x + 4y = 10$.
\begin{aligned}2x + 4(1) &= 10 \\ 2x + 4 &= 10 \\ 2x &= 6 \\ x &= \boxed{3}\end{aligned}
